## SOLID Principles — The Foundation of Clean Object-Oriented Design

### What Problem Does SOLID Solve?
Without guiding principles, code becomes rigid (hard to change), fragile (changes break unrelated things), and immobile (impossible to reuse). SOLID gives you five rules that produce **testable, extensible, maintainable** code.

---

### S — Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)
> A class should have only ONE reason to change.

Every class owns exactly one job. If you can describe a class with "and" — it violates SRP.

### O — Open/Closed Principle (OCP)
> Open for extension, closed for modification.

Add new behavior by writing new code (new classes), not by editing existing classes.

### L — Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)
> Subtypes must be substitutable for their base types without altering correctness.

If `Bird` has `fly()`, then `Penguin extends Bird` breaks LSP because penguins cannot fly. Fix: split into `FlyingBird` and `NonFlyingBird`.

### I — Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
> No client should be forced to depend on methods it does not use.

Split fat interfaces into focused ones. A `Printer` interface should not force a simple printer to implement `fax()` and `scan()`.

### D — Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)
> High-level modules should not depend on low-level modules. Both should depend on abstractions.

Don't instantiate dependencies directly — accept them via constructor injection.

---

### UML Class Diagram (Mermaid)

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class Shape {
        <<interface>>
        +area() double
    }
    class Circle {
        -radius: double
        +area() double
    }
    class Rectangle {
        -width: double
        -height: double
        +area() double
    }
    class AreaCalculator {
        +totalArea(shapes: Shape[]) double
    }
    Shape <|.. Circle : implements
    Shape <|.. Rectangle : implements
    AreaCalculator --> Shape : depends on abstraction
```

---

### Java Implementation (Compilable)

```java
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

public class Main {

    // ---- SRP: Each class has one responsibility ----
    interface Shape {
        double area();
    }

    // ---- OCP: Add shapes without modifying AreaCalculator ----
    static class Circle implements Shape {
        private final double radius;
        Circle(double radius) { this.radius = radius; }
        public double area() { return Math.PI * radius * radius; }
    }

    static class Rectangle implements Shape {
        private final double width, height;
        Rectangle(double w, double h) { this.width = w; this.height = h; }
        public double area() { return width * height; }
    }

    // ---- LSP: Any Shape subtype works here ----
    static class AreaCalculator {
        public double totalArea(List<Shape> shapes) {
            double sum = 0;
            for (Shape s : shapes) sum += s.area();
            return sum;
        }
    }

    // ---- ISP: Segregated interfaces ----
    interface Printable { void print(); }
    interface Scannable { void scan(); }

    static class SimplePrinter implements Printable {
        public void print() { System.out.println("Printing document..."); }
    }

    static class MultiFunctionPrinter implements Printable, Scannable {
        public void print() { System.out.println("Printing document..."); }
        public void scan() { System.out.println("Scanning document..."); }
    }

    // ---- DIP: Depend on abstractions ----
    interface Database {
        void save(String data);
    }

    static class MySQLDatabase implements Database {
        public void save(String data) { System.out.println("MySQL saving: " + data); }
    }

    static class InMemoryDatabase implements Database {
        public void save(String data) { System.out.println("InMemory saving: " + data); }
    }

    static class OrderService {
        private final Database db;
        OrderService(Database db) { this.db = db; }
        void createOrder(String order) { db.save(order); }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<Shape> shapes = new ArrayList<>();
        shapes.add(new Circle(5));
        shapes.add(new Rectangle(4, 6));
        AreaCalculator calc = new AreaCalculator();
        System.out.println("Total area: " + calc.totalArea(shapes));

        new SimplePrinter().print();
        MultiFunctionPrinter mfp = new MultiFunctionPrinter();
        mfp.print();
        mfp.scan();

        OrderService svc1 = new OrderService(new MySQLDatabase());
        svc1.createOrder("Order-001");
        OrderService svc2 = new OrderService(new InMemoryDatabase());
        svc2.createOrder("Order-002");
    }
}
```

---

### Python Implementation (Runnable)

```python
from abc import ABC, abstractmethod
import math

class Shape(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def area(self) -> float: ...

class Circle(Shape):
    def __init__(self, radius: float):
        self.radius = radius
    def area(self) -> float:
        return math.pi * self.radius ** 2

class Rectangle(Shape):
    def __init__(self, width: float, height: float):
        self.width = width
        self.height = height
    def area(self) -> float:
        return self.width * self.height

class AreaCalculator:
    @staticmethod
    def total_area(shapes: list) -> float:
        return sum(s.area() for s in shapes)

# ISP: Segregated interfaces
class Printable(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def print_doc(self): ...

class Scannable(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def scan_doc(self): ...

class SimplePrinter(Printable):
    def print_doc(self):
        print("Printing document...")

class MultiFunctionPrinter(Printable, Scannable):
    def print_doc(self):
        print("Printing document...")
    def scan_doc(self):
        print("Scanning document...")

# DIP: Depend on abstractions
class Database(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def save(self, data: str): ...

class MySQLDatabase(Database):
    def save(self, data: str):
        print(f"MySQL saving: {data}")

class InMemoryDatabase(Database):
    def save(self, data: str):
        print(f"InMemory saving: {data}")

class OrderService:
    def __init__(self, db: Database):
        self.db = db
    def create_order(self, order: str):
        self.db.save(order)

if __name__ == "__main__":
    shapes = [Circle(5), Rectangle(4, 6)]
    print(f"Total area: {AreaCalculator.total_area(shapes):.2f}")
    SimplePrinter().print_doc()
    MultiFunctionPrinter().print_doc()
    OrderService(MySQLDatabase()).create_order("Order-001")
    OrderService(InMemoryDatabase()).create_order("Order-002")
```

---

### When to Use
- **Always.** SOLID should guide every class you write.
- SRP and DIP are the most impactful in daily work.
- OCP is critical when designing libraries or frameworks.

### When NOT to Use
- Don't over-apply to trivial scripts or one-off utilities.
- YAGNI still applies: don't create 5 interfaces for code that will never change.

---

### Real-World Examples
| Principle | Real-World Example |
|-----------|-------------------|
| SRP | Separate UserService, EmailService, LoggingService instead of one God class |
| OCP | Plugin systems (VS Code extensions, Webpack loaders) |
| LSP | Java Collections — ArrayList and LinkedList both implement List correctly |
| ISP | Java's Readable, Appendable, Closeable instead of one I/O interface |
| DIP | Spring Framework's dependency injection container |

---

### Interview Questions
1. **Explain SRP with an example.** A UserService that handles CRUD AND sends emails violates SRP. Split into UserService + EmailService.
2. **What's the difference between SRP and ISP?** SRP is about classes having one reason to change. ISP is about interfaces — don't force implementors to provide methods they don't need.
3. **How does DIP enable testing?** By depending on abstractions (interfaces), you can inject mock/stub implementations in tests.
4. **Give an example of LSP violation.** Square extending Rectangle breaks LSP — setting width on Square must also set height, breaking Rectangle's contract.
5. **How do OCP and Strategy pattern relate?** Strategy implements OCP — add new algorithms by creating new strategy classes, never modifying the context.

## Singleton Pattern — Ensuring Exactly One Instance

### What Problem Does It Solve?
Some resources should exist only once: database connection pools, configuration managers, logging services. Singleton guarantees exactly one instance with a global access point.

---

### UML Class Diagram (Mermaid)

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class Singleton {
        -instance: Singleton$
        -Singleton()
        +getInstance()$ Singleton
        +operation() void
    }
    note for Singleton "Private constructor prevents\nexternal instantiation.\nStatic getInstance() returns\nthe single instance."
```

---

### Java Implementation (Compilable)

```java
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

public class Main {

    // === Enum Singleton (Joshua Bloch recommended) ===
    enum ConfigManager {
        INSTANCE;

        private final Map<String, String> config = new HashMap<>();

        ConfigManager() {
            config.put("db.host", "localhost");
            config.put("db.port", "5432");
            config.put("app.name", "GuruSishya");
        }

        public String get(String key) {
            return config.getOrDefault(key, "NOT_FOUND");
        }

        public void set(String key, String value) {
            config.put(key, value);
        }
    }

    // === Double-Checked Locking Singleton ===
    static class DatabasePool {
        private static volatile DatabasePool instance;
        private final String connectionUrl;

        private DatabasePool(String url) {
            this.connectionUrl = url;
            System.out.println("  Creating DB pool: " + url);
        }

        public static DatabasePool getInstance() {
            if (instance == null) {
                synchronized (DatabasePool.class) {
                    if (instance == null) {
                        instance = new DatabasePool("jdbc:postgresql://localhost/mydb");
                    }
                }
            }
            return instance;
        }

        public String getUrl() { return connectionUrl; }
    }

    // === Bill Pugh Holder Idiom ===
    static class Logger {
        private Logger() { System.out.println("  Logger initialized"); }

        private static class Holder {
            static final Logger INSTANCE = new Logger();
        }

        public static Logger getInstance() { return Holder.INSTANCE; }

        public void log(String msg) {
            System.out.println("  [LOG] " + msg);
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("=== Enum Singleton ===");
        System.out.println("  App: " + ConfigManager.INSTANCE.get("app.name"));
        ConfigManager.INSTANCE.set("debug", "true");
        System.out.println("  Debug: " + ConfigManager.INSTANCE.get("debug"));

        System.out.println("\n=== Double-Checked Locking ===");
        DatabasePool pool1 = DatabasePool.getInstance();
        DatabasePool pool2 = DatabasePool.getInstance();
        System.out.println("  Same pool? " + (pool1 == pool2));

        System.out.println("\n=== Bill Pugh Holder ===");
        Logger.getInstance().log("Application started");
        System.out.println("  Same instance? " + (Logger.getInstance() == Logger.getInstance()));
    }
}
```

---

### Python Implementation (Runnable)

```python
import threading

# === Thread-Safe Singleton using __new__ ===
class DatabasePool:
    _instance = None
    _lock = threading.Lock()

    def __new__(cls, url: str = "postgresql://localhost/mydb"):
        if cls._instance is None:
            with cls._lock:
                if cls._instance is None:
                    cls._instance = super().__new__(cls)
                    cls._instance.url = url
                    print(f"  Creating DB pool: {url}")
        return cls._instance

    def get_connection(self):
        return f"Connection to {self.url}"

# === Module-level Singleton (Pythonic) ===
class _Config:
    def __init__(self):
        self._data = {"db.host": "localhost", "db.port": "5432", "app.name": "GuruSishya"}
    def get(self, key: str) -> str:
        return self._data.get(key, "NOT_FOUND")
    def set(self, key: str, value: str):
        self._data[key] = value

config = _Config()  # Module-level — Python imports are cached

# === Decorator Singleton ===
def singleton(cls):
    instances = {}
    def get_instance(*args, **kwargs):
        if cls not in instances:
            instances[cls] = cls(*args, **kwargs)
        return instances[cls]
    return get_instance

@singleton
class Logger:
    def __init__(self):
        print("  Logger initialized")
    def log(self, msg: str):
        print(f"  [LOG] {msg}")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    print("=== Thread-Safe Singleton ===")
    pool1 = DatabasePool()
    pool2 = DatabasePool("ignored")
    print(f"  Same pool? {pool1 is pool2}")
    print(f"  {pool1.get_connection()}")

    print("\n=== Module Singleton ===")
    print(f"  App: {config.get('app.name')}")

    print("\n=== Decorator Singleton ===")
    logger1 = Logger()
    logger2 = Logger()
    print(f"  Same logger? {logger1 is logger2}")
    logger1.log("Application started")
```

---

### When to Use
- Database connection pools (expensive to create, shared resource)
- Application configuration (loaded once, read everywhere)
- Logging services (single output stream)
- Hardware interface access (one printer spooler)

### When NOT to Use
- **Unit testing**: Global state makes tests order-dependent
- **Multitenant systems**: Each tenant may need its own instance
- **When DI is available**: Spring, NestJS handle lifecycle better
- **Microservices**: Each service has its own state

---

### Real-World Examples
| System | Singleton Use |
|--------|--------------|
| Java Runtime | `Runtime.getRuntime()` — one JVM runtime |
| Spring | All beans are singleton-scoped by default |
| Python logging | `logging.getLogger(name)` caches per name |
| Android | `Application` class — one per app process |
| Node.js | Module cache — `require()` returns same object |

---

### Interview Questions
1. **Why is Singleton considered an anti-pattern?** Global mutable state makes unit tests difficult. Violates SRP (manages lifecycle AND business logic). Hides dependencies. Prefer DI.
2. **Thread-safe Singleton in Java?** Three approaches: Enum (JVM guaranteed), Double-checked locking (volatile + synchronized), Bill Pugh Holder (static inner class).
3. **Can Singleton be broken?** Yes — reflection, serialization/deserialization, cloning. Enum prevents all three.
4. **Singleton vs static class?** Singleton implements interfaces, supports polymorphism, lazy init. Static classes cannot.
5. **Spring Singletons?** One instance per IoC container, not per JVM. DI-managed, not class-enforced.

## Factory Pattern — Creating Objects Without Specifying Exact Classes

### What Problem Does It Solve?
When object creation involves complex logic or conditional decisions, Factory encapsulates creation. The client says "I need a notification sender" — the factory decides which concrete class.

---

### UML Class Diagram (Mermaid)

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class Notification {
        <<interface>>
        +send(message: String) void
    }
    class EmailNotification {
        +send(message: String) void
    }
    class SMSNotification {
        +send(message: String) void
    }
    class PushNotification {
        +send(message: String) void
    }
    class NotificationFactory {
        +create(channel: String)$ Notification
    }
    Notification <|.. EmailNotification : implements
    Notification <|.. SMSNotification : implements
    Notification <|.. PushNotification : implements
    NotificationFactory ..> Notification : creates
```

---

### Java Implementation (Compilable)

```java
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.function.Supplier;

public class Main {

    interface Notification {
        void send(String message);
    }

    static class EmailNotification implements Notification {
        public void send(String message) {
            System.out.println("[EMAIL] user@example.com | " + message);
        }
    }

    static class SMSNotification implements Notification {
        public void send(String message) {
            System.out.println("[SMS] +1-555-0100 | " + message);
        }
    }

    static class PushNotification implements Notification {
        public void send(String message) {
            System.out.println("[PUSH] device-001 | " + message);
        }
    }

    // === Simple Factory ===
    static class NotificationFactory {
        public static Notification create(String channel) {
            switch (channel.toLowerCase()) {
                case "email": return new EmailNotification();
                case "sms":   return new SMSNotification();
                case "push":  return new PushNotification();
                default: throw new IllegalArgumentException("Unknown: " + channel);
            }
        }
    }

    // === Registry Factory (OCP compliant) ===
    static class NotificationRegistry {
        private static final Map<String, Supplier<Notification>> registry = new HashMap<>();

        public static void register(String ch, Supplier<Notification> creator) {
            registry.put(ch.toLowerCase(), creator);
        }

        public static Notification create(String ch) {
            Supplier<Notification> creator = registry.get(ch.toLowerCase());
            if (creator == null) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Unknown: " + ch);
            return creator.get();
        }
    }

    // === Abstract Factory ===
    interface UIFactory {
        String createButton();
        String createInput();
    }

    static class DarkThemeFactory implements UIFactory {
        public String createButton() { return "[Dark Button]"; }
        public String createInput() { return "[Dark Input]"; }
    }

    static class LightThemeFactory implements UIFactory {
        public String createButton() { return "[Light Button]"; }
        public String createInput() { return "[Light Input]"; }
    }

    static void renderUI(UIFactory factory) {
        System.out.println("  Button: " + factory.createButton());
        System.out.println("  Input:  " + factory.createInput());
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("=== Simple Factory ===");
        NotificationFactory.create("email").send("Welcome!");
        NotificationFactory.create("sms").send("Code: 1234");
        NotificationFactory.create("push").send("New message");

        System.out.println("\n=== Registry Factory ===");
        NotificationRegistry.register("email", EmailNotification::new);
        NotificationRegistry.register("sms", SMSNotification::new);
        NotificationRegistry.register("push", PushNotification::new);
        NotificationRegistry.create("email").send("Registry works!");

        System.out.println("\n=== Abstract Factory (Dark) ===");
        renderUI(new DarkThemeFactory());
        System.out.println("=== Abstract Factory (Light) ===");
        renderUI(new LightThemeFactory());
    }
}
```

---

### Python Implementation (Runnable)

```python
from abc import ABC, abstractmethod
from typing import Callable

class Notification(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def send(self, message: str) -> None: ...

class EmailNotification(Notification):
    def send(self, message: str):
        print(f"[EMAIL] user@example.com | {message}")

class SMSNotification(Notification):
    def send(self, message: str):
        print(f"[SMS] +1-555-0100 | {message}")

class PushNotification(Notification):
    def send(self, message: str):
        print(f"[PUSH] device-001 | {message}")

# Simple Factory
class NotificationFactory:
    _map = {"email": EmailNotification, "sms": SMSNotification, "push": PushNotification}

    @staticmethod
    def create(channel: str) -> Notification:
        cls = NotificationFactory._map.get(channel.lower())
        if not cls:
            raise ValueError(f"Unknown channel: {channel}")
        return cls()

# Registry Factory (OCP compliant)
class NotificationRegistry:
    _registry: dict[str, Callable[[], Notification]] = {}

    @classmethod
    def register(cls, channel: str, creator: Callable[[], Notification]):
        cls._registry[channel.lower()] = creator

    @classmethod
    def create(cls, channel: str) -> Notification:
        creator = cls._registry.get(channel.lower())
        if not creator:
            raise ValueError(f"Unknown: {channel}")
        return creator()

# Abstract Factory
class UIFactory(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def create_button(self) -> str: ...
    @abstractmethod
    def create_input(self) -> str: ...

class DarkThemeFactory(UIFactory):
    def create_button(self) -> str: return "[Dark Button]"
    def create_input(self) -> str: return "[Dark Input]"

class LightThemeFactory(UIFactory):
    def create_button(self) -> str: return "[Light Button]"
    def create_input(self) -> str: return "[Light Input]"

def render_ui(factory: UIFactory):
    print(f"  Button: {factory.create_button()}")
    print(f"  Input:  {factory.create_input()}")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    print("=== Simple Factory ===")
    NotificationFactory.create("email").send("Welcome!")
    NotificationFactory.create("sms").send("Code: 1234")

    print("\n=== Registry Factory ===")
    NotificationRegistry.register("email", EmailNotification)
    NotificationRegistry.register("sms", SMSNotification)
    NotificationRegistry.create("email").send("Registry works!")

    print("\n=== Abstract Factory (Dark) ===")
    render_ui(DarkThemeFactory())
    print("=== Abstract Factory (Light) ===")
    render_ui(LightThemeFactory())
```

---

### When to Use
- Object creation depends on runtime conditions (payment gateways, notification channels)
- Decouple creation logic from usage
- Abstract Factory when you need families of related objects (UI themes)

### When NOT to Use
- Only one product type with trivial creation — just use `new`
- Product types known at compile time and won't change

---

### Real-World Examples
| System | Factory Use |
|--------|------------|
| JDBC | `DriverManager.getConnection()` — returns MySQL/Postgres driver |
| Spring | `BeanFactory` creates and manages bean instances |
| React | `React.createElement()` — factory for virtual DOM nodes |
| SLF4J | `LoggerFactory.getLogger()` — returns appropriate logger impl |

---

### Interview Questions
1. **Simple vs Abstract Factory?** Simple creates one product type. Abstract creates families of related products (Button + Input + Modal as a matching set).
2. **Factory supports OCP how?** Registry factory — add new product by registering a creator, no modification of factory code.
3. **Factory vs Builder?** Factory: type varies. Builder: configuration varies. Factory answers 'which class?'; Builder answers 'which options?'
4. **Factory Method vs Simple Factory?** Factory Method uses inheritance — subclass overrides creation method. Simple Factory uses conditional logic in a static method.
5. **Factory and DIP?** Factory achieves DIP — client depends on abstract product interface, factory handles concrete instantiation.

## Builder Pattern — Constructing Complex Objects Step by Step

### What Problem Does It Solve?
When an object has many parameters (especially optional ones), constructors become unwieldy. Builder provides a fluent, readable API for step-by-step construction. Eliminates "telescoping constructor" anti-pattern.

---

### UML Class Diagram (Mermaid)

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class HttpRequest {
        -method: String
        -url: String
        -headers: Map
        -body: String
        -timeout: int
    }
    class HttpRequestBuilder {
        +method(m: String) Builder
        +url(u: String) Builder
        +header(k: String, v: String) Builder
        +body(b: String) Builder
        +timeout(t: int) Builder
        +build() HttpRequest
    }
    HttpRequestBuilder ..> HttpRequest : builds
```

---

### Java Implementation (Compilable)

```java
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

public class Main {

    // === HttpRequest with Builder ===
    static class HttpRequest {
        private final String method;
        private final String url;
        private final Map<String, String> headers;
        private final String body;
        private final int timeoutMs;

        private HttpRequest(Builder b) {
            this.method = b.method;
            this.url = b.url;
            this.headers = new HashMap<>(b.headers);
            this.body = b.body;
            this.timeoutMs = b.timeoutMs;
        }

        public String toString() {
            return method + " " + url + " headers=" + headers
                + " body=" + (body != null ? body : "null")
                + " timeout=" + timeoutMs + "ms";
        }

        static class Builder {
            private String method = "GET";
            private String url = "";
            private final Map<String, String> headers = new HashMap<>();
            private String body = null;
            private int timeoutMs = 30000;

            public Builder method(String m) { this.method = m; return this; }
            public Builder url(String u) { this.url = u; return this; }
            public Builder header(String k, String v) { headers.put(k, v); return this; }
            public Builder body(String b) { this.body = b; return this; }
            public Builder timeout(int ms) { this.timeoutMs = ms; return this; }

            public HttpRequest build() {
                if (url.isEmpty()) throw new IllegalStateException("URL required");
                return new HttpRequest(this);
            }
        }
    }

    // === SQL Query Builder ===
    static class QueryBuilder {
        private String table = "";
        private final List<String> columns = new ArrayList<>();
        private final List<String> conditions = new ArrayList<>();
        private String orderBy = null;
        private Integer limit = null;

        public QueryBuilder from(String t) { this.table = t; return this; }
        public QueryBuilder select(String... cols) {
            for (String c : cols) columns.add(c);
            return this;
        }
        public QueryBuilder where(String c) { conditions.add(c); return this; }
        public QueryBuilder orderBy(String f) { this.orderBy = f; return this; }
        public QueryBuilder limit(int n) { this.limit = n; return this; }

        public String build() {
            StringBuilder sql = new StringBuilder("SELECT ");
            sql.append(columns.isEmpty() ? "*" : String.join(", ", columns));
            sql.append(" FROM ").append(table);
            if (!conditions.isEmpty())
                sql.append(" WHERE ").append(String.join(" AND ", conditions));
            if (orderBy != null) sql.append(" ORDER BY ").append(orderBy);
            if (limit != null) sql.append(" LIMIT ").append(limit);
            return sql.toString();
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("=== HTTP Request Builder ===");
        HttpRequest get = new HttpRequest.Builder()
            .url("https://api.example.com/users")
            .header("Authorization", "Bearer token123")
            .header("Accept", "application/json")
            .timeout(5000)
            .build();
        System.out.println(get);

        HttpRequest post = new HttpRequest.Builder()
            .method("POST")
            .url("https://api.example.com/users")
            .header("Content-Type", "application/json")
            .body("{\"name\": \"Alice\"}")
            .build();
        System.out.println(post);

        System.out.println("\n=== SQL Query Builder ===");
        String q1 = new QueryBuilder()
            .from("users").select("id", "name", "email")
            .where("age > 18").where("active = true")
            .orderBy("created_at DESC").limit(10)
            .build();
        System.out.println(q1);

        String q2 = new QueryBuilder()
            .from("products").where("price < 100").build();
        System.out.println(q2);
    }
}
```

---

### Python Implementation (Runnable)

```python
from dataclasses import dataclass, field

@dataclass(frozen=True)
class HttpRequest:
    method: str
    url: str
    headers: dict
    body: str | None
    timeout_ms: int

class HttpRequestBuilder:
    def __init__(self):
        self._method = "GET"
        self._url = ""
        self._headers: dict[str, str] = {}
        self._body: str | None = None
        self._timeout_ms = 30000

    def method(self, m: str): self._method = m; return self
    def url(self, u: str): self._url = u; return self
    def header(self, k: str, v: str): self._headers[k] = v; return self
    def body(self, b: str): self._body = b; return self
    def timeout(self, ms: int): self._timeout_ms = ms; return self

    def build(self) -> HttpRequest:
        if not self._url:
            raise ValueError("URL is required")
        return HttpRequest(self._method, self._url, dict(self._headers),
                          self._body, self._timeout_ms)

class QueryBuilder:
    def __init__(self):
        self._table = ""
        self._columns: list[str] = []
        self._conditions: list[str] = []
        self._order_by: str | None = None
        self._limit: int | None = None

    def from_table(self, t: str): self._table = t; return self
    def select(self, *cols: str): self._columns.extend(cols); return self
    def where(self, c: str): self._conditions.append(c); return self
    def order_by(self, f: str): self._order_by = f; return self
    def limit(self, n: int): self._limit = n; return self

    def build(self) -> str:
        cols = ", ".join(self._columns) if self._columns else "*"
        sql = f"SELECT {cols} FROM {self._table}"
        if self._conditions:
            sql += f" WHERE {' AND '.join(self._conditions)}"
        if self._order_by:
            sql += f" ORDER BY {self._order_by}"
        if self._limit is not None:
            sql += f" LIMIT {self._limit}"
        return sql

if __name__ == "__main__":
    print("=== HTTP Request Builder ===")
    get = (HttpRequestBuilder()
        .url("https://api.example.com/users")
        .header("Authorization", "Bearer token123")
        .timeout(5000).build())
    print(get)

    post = (HttpRequestBuilder()
        .method("POST").url("https://api.example.com/users")
        .header("Content-Type", "application/json")
        .body('{"name": "Alice"}').build())
    print(post)

    print("\n=== SQL Query Builder ===")
    q1 = (QueryBuilder().from_table("users").select("id", "name", "email")
        .where("age > 18").where("active = true")
        .order_by("created_at DESC").limit(10).build())
    print(q1)

    q2 = QueryBuilder().from_table("products").where("price < 100").build()
    print(q2)
```

---

### When to Use
- Objects with 4+ parameters, especially optional ones
- Object construction involves multiple steps or validations
- SQL query builders, HTTP request builders, test data builders
- You want immutable objects with a readable creation API

### When NOT to Use
- Objects with 1-3 required parameters — constructor is clearer
- Languages with named parameters (Kotlin, Python kwargs) reduce the need
- Simple value objects where factory method suffices

---

### Real-World Examples
| System | Builder Use |
|--------|-----------|
| Java | `StringBuilder`, `Stream.builder()` |
| OkHttp | `Request.Builder().url().header().build()` |
| Lombok | `@Builder` generates builder automatically |
| Protobuf | All protobuf messages use builders |
| Testing | `UserBuilder.aUser().withName("Alice").build()` |

---

### Interview Questions
1. **Builder vs Factory?** Factory decides WHICH class (type varies). Builder decides HOW to configure one class (options vary).
2. **Why Builder over telescoping constructors?** Readability, validation, optional params without null-passing, immutable results.
3. **Director pattern?** Optional class that encapsulates common build sequences. E.g., `HttpDirector.createAuthGet(url, token)`.
4. **Lombok @Builder?** Generates Builder class at compile time via annotation processing — zero boilerplate.
5. **Builder in functional languages?** Kotlin named params reduce the need. Builder is most valuable in Java.

## Observer Pattern (Pub/Sub) — When State Changes, Everyone Knows

### What Problem Does It Solve?
When one object changes state, multiple others need to react — without tight coupling. Observer lets publishers emit events without knowing who listens, and subscribers react without knowing who published.

---

### UML Class Diagram (Mermaid)

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class EventEmitter {
        -listeners: Map
        +on(event, listener) void
        +off(event, listener) void
        +emit(event, data) void
    }
    class StockObserver {
        <<interface>>
        +onPriceChange(ticker, old, new) void
    }
    class PriceAlert {
        +onPriceChange(ticker, old, new) void
    }
    class TradingBot {
        +onPriceChange(ticker, old, new) void
    }
    class AuditLogger {
        +onPriceChange(ticker, old, new) void
    }
    StockObserver <|.. PriceAlert : implements
    StockObserver <|.. TradingBot : implements
    StockObserver <|.. AuditLogger : implements
```

---

### Java Implementation (Compilable)

```java
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.function.Consumer;

public class Main {

    // === Generic EventEmitter ===
    static class EventEmitter {
        private final Map<String, List<Consumer<Object>>> listeners = new HashMap<>();

        public void on(String event, Consumer<Object> listener) {
            listeners.computeIfAbsent(event, k -> new ArrayList<>()).add(listener);
        }

        public void off(String event, Consumer<Object> listener) {
            List<Consumer<Object>> list = listeners.get(event);
            if (list != null) list.remove(listener);
        }

        public void emit(String event, Object data) {
            List<Consumer<Object>> list = listeners.get(event);
            if (list != null) for (Consumer<Object> l : list) l.accept(data);
        }
    }

    // === Stock Exchange Observer ===
    interface StockObserver {
        void onPriceChange(String ticker, double oldPrice, double newPrice);
    }

    static class StockExchange {
        private final Map<String, Double> prices = new HashMap<>();
        private final List<StockObserver> observers = new ArrayList<>();

        public void addObserver(StockObserver obs) { observers.add(obs); }

        public void updatePrice(String ticker, double newPrice) {
            double oldPrice = prices.getOrDefault(ticker, 0.0);
            prices.put(ticker, newPrice);
            for (StockObserver obs : observers)
                obs.onPriceChange(ticker, oldPrice, newPrice);
        }
    }

    static class PriceAlert implements StockObserver {
        private final double threshold;
        PriceAlert(double t) { this.threshold = t; }

        public void onPriceChange(String ticker, double oldP, double newP) {
            if (oldP > 0) {
                double change = Math.abs(newP - oldP) / oldP * 100;
                if (change > threshold)
                    System.out.printf("  ALERT: %s moved %.1f%%  $%.2f->$%.2f%n",
                        ticker, change, oldP, newP);
            }
        }
    }

    static class TradingBot implements StockObserver {
        public void onPriceChange(String ticker, double oldP, double newP) {
            if (oldP > 0 && newP < oldP * 0.95)
                System.out.printf("  BOT: BUY %s at $%.2f (dip)%n", ticker, newP);
            else if (oldP > 0 && newP > oldP * 1.10)
                System.out.printf("  BOT: SELL %s at $%.2f (gain)%n", ticker, newP);
        }
    }

    static class AuditLog implements StockObserver {
        public void onPriceChange(String ticker, double oldP, double newP) {
            System.out.printf("  LOG: %s $%.2f -> $%.2f%n", ticker, oldP, newP);
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("=== Generic EventEmitter ===");
        EventEmitter bus = new EventEmitter();
        bus.on("userCreated", d -> System.out.println("  Welcome email: " + d));
        bus.on("userCreated", d -> System.out.println("  Audit log: " + d));
        bus.emit("userCreated", "Alice");

        System.out.println("\n=== Stock Exchange ===");
        StockExchange exchange = new StockExchange();
        exchange.addObserver(new PriceAlert(5.0));
        exchange.addObserver(new TradingBot());
        exchange.addObserver(new AuditLog());

        exchange.updatePrice("AAPL", 150.00);
        exchange.updatePrice("AAPL", 142.00);
        exchange.updatePrice("GOOGL", 2800.00);
        exchange.updatePrice("GOOGL", 3100.00);
    }
}
```

