### Python Implementation (Runnable)

```python
from abc import ABC, abstractmethod

# === Payment Adapter ===
class PaymentProcessor(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def charge(self, amount: float, currency: str) -> bool: ...

class LegacyGateway:
    def make_payment(self, cents: int, currency_code: str) -> int:
        print(f"  Legacy: charging {cents} cents ({currency_code})")
        return 1

class LegacyAdapter(PaymentProcessor):
    def __init__(self, legacy: LegacyGateway):
        self.legacy = legacy

    def charge(self, amount: float, currency: str) -> bool:
        cents = int(amount * 100)
        return self.legacy.make_payment(cents, currency) == 1

# === API Response Adapter ===
class ExternalUser:
    def __init__(self, user_name: str, email_address: str, is_active: int):
        self.user_name = user_name
        self.email_address = email_address
        self.is_active = is_active

class User:
    def __init__(self, name: str, email: str, active: bool):
        self.name = name
        self.email = email
        self.active = active

    def __repr__(self):
        return f"User(name='{self.name}', email='{self.email}', active={self.active})"

def adapt_user(ext: ExternalUser) -> User:
    return User(name=ext.user_name, email=ext.email_address, active=ext.is_active == 1)

# === Duck Typing Adapter (Pythonic) ===
class OldLogger:
    def write_log(self, level: str, msg: str):
        print(f"  [{level}] {msg}")

class LoggerAdapter:
    # Adapts OldLogger to work like standard logging.
    def __init__(self, old: OldLogger):
        self._old = old
    def info(self, msg): self._old.write_log("INFO", msg)
    def error(self, msg): self._old.write_log("ERROR", msg)
    def warning(self, msg): self._old.write_log("WARN", msg)

if __name__ == "__main__":
    print("=== Payment Adapter ===")
    processor = LegacyAdapter(LegacyGateway())
    print(f"  Success: {processor.charge(29.99, 'USD')}")

    print("\n=== API Response Adapter ===")
    ext = ExternalUser("alice_smith", "alice@example.com", 1)
    print(f"  {adapt_user(ext)}")

    print("\n=== Logger Adapter ===")
    logger = LoggerAdapter(OldLogger())
    logger.info("Application started")
    logger.error("Something went wrong")
```

---

### When to Use
- Integrating third-party APIs with different interfaces
- Wrapping legacy systems to work with modern code
- Converting data formats (XML to JSON, snake_case to camelCase)
- Making incompatible libraries work together

### When NOT to Use
- When you can modify the source interface directly
- When the adaptation is trivial (just rename a method)
- When Facade would be more appropriate (simplifying, not translating)

---

### Real-World Examples
| System | Adapter Use |
|--------|-----------|
| JDBC | Adapts various DB protocols to standard JDBC interface |
| SLF4J | Adapts Log4j, Logback, JUL to common logging API |
| React | Wrapper components adapting third-party UI libraries |
| Arrays.asList() | Adapts array to List interface |
| REST-to-GraphQL | Adapter layers translating between API styles |

---

### Interview Questions
1. **Adapter vs Facade?** Adapter: translates ONE interface to ANOTHER (1-to-1 mapping). Facade: simplifies a COMPLEX SUBSYSTEM behind a simple API (many-to-1).
2. **Class vs Object Adapter?** Class adapter uses multiple inheritance (extends both). Object adapter uses composition (wraps the adaptee). Object adapter is preferred — more flexible.
3. **When to use Adapter in microservices?** Anti-corruption layer — adapter between your service and external APIs, preventing external data models from leaking into your domain.
4. **Adapter vs Decorator?** Adapter changes the interface (different input/output types). Decorator preserves the interface (same types, adds behavior).
5. **Real-world Adapter example?** Power adapters (US to EU plug). In software: SLF4J adapts Log4j/Logback to a common API. JDBC adapts MySQL/Postgres to standard interface.

## Facade Pattern — Simplify Complex Subsystems

### What Problem Does It Solve?
Complex systems have many interacting components. Facade provides ONE simple method that orchestrates the complexity. Client doesn't need to know about inventory, payment, shipping, and notification services — just `placeOrder()`.

---

### UML Class Diagram (Mermaid)

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class OrderFacade {
        +placeOrder(user, items, payment) OrderResult
    }
    class InventoryService {
        +checkStock(items) boolean
        +reserve(items) void
    }
    class PaymentService {
        +charge(user, amount) boolean
    }
    class ShippingService {
        +createShipment(address, items) String
    }
    class NotificationService {
        +sendConfirmation(email, tracking) void
    }
    OrderFacade --> InventoryService
    OrderFacade --> PaymentService
    OrderFacade --> ShippingService
    OrderFacade --> NotificationService
```

---

### Java Implementation (Compilable)

```java
import java.util.List;

public class Main {

    // === Subsystem Classes ===
    static class InventoryService {
        public boolean checkStock(List<String> items) {
            System.out.println("  Inventory: checking stock for " + items);
            return true;
        }
        public void reserve(List<String> items) {
            System.out.println("  Inventory: reserved " + items);
        }
        public void release(List<String> items) {
            System.out.println("  Inventory: released " + items);
        }
    }

    static class PaymentService {
        public boolean charge(String userId, double amount) {
            System.out.printf("  Payment: charged $%.2f to %s%n", amount, userId);
            return true;
        }
    }

    static class ShippingService {
        public String createShipment(String address, List<String> items) {
            String tracking = "TRK-" + System.currentTimeMillis();
            System.out.println("  Shipping: created shipment " + tracking);
            return tracking;
        }
    }

    static class NotificationService {
        public void sendEmail(String email, String subject, String body) {
            System.out.println("  Notification: sent '" + subject + "' to " + email);
        }
    }

    // === Facade ===
    static class OrderFacade {
        private final InventoryService inventory = new InventoryService();
        private final PaymentService payment = new PaymentService();
        private final ShippingService shipping = new ShippingService();
        private final NotificationService notification = new NotificationService();

        public String placeOrder(String userId, String email,
                                  String address, List<String> items, double total) {
            // Step 1: Check stock
            if (!inventory.checkStock(items)) {
                throw new RuntimeException("Items out of stock");
            }

            // Step 2: Reserve inventory
            inventory.reserve(items);

            // Step 3: Charge payment
            if (!payment.charge(userId, total)) {
                inventory.release(items);
                throw new RuntimeException("Payment failed");
            }

            // Step 4: Ship
            String tracking = shipping.createShipment(address, items);

            // Step 5: Notify
            notification.sendEmail(email, "Order Confirmed",
                "Tracking: " + tracking);

            return tracking;
        }
    }

    // === Analytics Facade ===
    static class MixpanelClient {
        void track(String event) { System.out.println("  Mixpanel: " + event); }
    }
    static class AmplitudeClient {
        void logEvent(String event) { System.out.println("  Amplitude: " + event); }
    }

    static class AnalyticsFacade {
        private final MixpanelClient mixpanel = new MixpanelClient();
        private final AmplitudeClient amplitude = new AmplitudeClient();

        public void track(String event) {
            mixpanel.track(event);
            amplitude.logEvent(event);
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("=== Order Facade ===");
        OrderFacade orders = new OrderFacade();
        String tracking = orders.placeOrder(
            "user-123", "alice@example.com",
            "123 Main St", List.of("Laptop", "Mouse"), 1299.99
        );
        System.out.println("  Order placed! Tracking: " + tracking);

        System.out.println("\n=== Analytics Facade ===");
        AnalyticsFacade analytics = new AnalyticsFacade();
        analytics.track("page_view");
        analytics.track("button_click");
    }
}
```

