---

### When to Use
- Complex multi-step workflows (order processing, deployment pipelines)
- Simplifying third-party library integration
- Providing a clean API for microservice orchestration
- When clients shouldn't know internal system structure

### When NOT to Use
- When the subsystem is already simple (unnecessary abstraction)
- When clients need fine-grained control over subsystem components
- When it becomes a God object (facade doing too much)

---

### Real-World Examples
| System | Facade Use |
|--------|-----------|
| jQuery | `$(selector)` — facade over complex DOM APIs |
| Spring Boot | Auto-configuration facades complex Spring setup |
| AWS SDK | High-level S3 client facades REST API complexity |
| React hooks | `useEffect` facades lifecycle method complexity |
| ORMs | Hibernate/SQLAlchemy facade over raw SQL |

---

### Interview Questions
1. **Facade vs Adapter?** Facade simplifies (many subsystems behind one API). Adapter translates (one interface to another). Facade reduces complexity; Adapter maintains it.
2. **Facade vs Mediator?** Facade provides unidirectional simplification. Mediator handles bidirectional communication between components.
3. **Can Facade violate SRP?** Yes — if it orchestrates too many unrelated workflows. Keep facades focused: OrderFacade, AnalyticsFacade, not AppFacade.
4. **Facade and testability?** Facade itself may be hard to test (many dependencies). Inject subsystem services via constructor for mockability.
5. **Facade in microservices?** API Gateway is a Facade — single entry point that routes to multiple microservices.

## Command Pattern — Encapsulate Requests as Objects

### What Problem Does It Solve?
Turn a method call into an object. This enables undo/redo, request queuing, logging, and macro recording. The request itself becomes a first-class citizen that can be stored, queued, replayed, or reversed.

---

### UML Class Diagram (Mermaid)

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class Command {
        <<interface>>
        +execute() void
        +undo() void
    }
    class AddTextCommand {
        -editor: TextEditor
        -text: String
        +execute() void
        +undo() void
    }
    class DeleteTextCommand {
        -editor: TextEditor
        -count: int
        -deleted: String
        +execute() void
        +undo() void
    }
    class CommandHistory {
        -history: Stack~Command~
        +executeCommand(cmd: Command) void
        +undo() void
    }
    Command <|.. AddTextCommand
    Command <|.. DeleteTextCommand
    CommandHistory --> Command
```

---

### Java Implementation (Compilable)

```java
import java.util.Stack;

public class Main {

    // === Text Editor with Undo/Redo ===
    static class TextEditor {
        private StringBuilder content = new StringBuilder();

        public void insert(String text) { content.append(text); }
        public void delete(int count) {
            int start = Math.max(0, content.length() - count);
            content.delete(start, content.length());
        }
        public String getContent() { return content.toString(); }
    }

    interface Command {
        void execute();
        void undo();
    }

    static class InsertCommand implements Command {
        private final TextEditor editor;
        private final String text;

        InsertCommand(TextEditor editor, String text) {
            this.editor = editor; this.text = text;
        }
        public void execute() { editor.insert(text); }
        public void undo() { editor.delete(text.length()); }
    }

    static class DeleteCommand implements Command {
        private final TextEditor editor;
        private final int count;
        private String deleted;

        DeleteCommand(TextEditor editor, int count) {
            this.editor = editor; this.count = count;
        }
        public void execute() {
            String content = editor.getContent();
            int start = Math.max(0, content.length() - count);
            deleted = content.substring(start);
            editor.delete(count);
        }
        public void undo() { editor.insert(deleted); }
    }

    static class CommandHistory {
        private final Stack<Command> undoStack = new Stack<>();
        private final Stack<Command> redoStack = new Stack<>();

        public void execute(Command cmd) {
            cmd.execute();
            undoStack.push(cmd);
            redoStack.clear();
        }

        public void undo() {
            if (!undoStack.isEmpty()) {
                Command cmd = undoStack.pop();
                cmd.undo();
                redoStack.push(cmd);
            }
        }

        public void redo() {
            if (!redoStack.isEmpty()) {
                Command cmd = redoStack.pop();
                cmd.execute();
                undoStack.push(cmd);
            }
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        TextEditor editor = new TextEditor();
        CommandHistory history = new CommandHistory();

        System.out.println("=== Text Editor with Undo/Redo ===");
        history.execute(new InsertCommand(editor, "Hello "));
        System.out.println("  After insert: '" + editor.getContent() + "'");

        history.execute(new InsertCommand(editor, "World"));
        System.out.println("  After insert: '" + editor.getContent() + "'");

        history.execute(new InsertCommand(editor, "!!!"));
        System.out.println("  After insert: '" + editor.getContent() + "'");

        history.undo();
        System.out.println("  After undo:   '" + editor.getContent() + "'");

        history.undo();
        System.out.println("  After undo:   '" + editor.getContent() + "'");

        history.redo();
        System.out.println("  After redo:   '" + editor.getContent() + "'");

        history.execute(new DeleteCommand(editor, 6));
        System.out.println("  After delete: '" + editor.getContent() + "'");

        history.undo();
        System.out.println("  After undo:   '" + editor.getContent() + "'");
    }
}
```

---

### Python Implementation (Runnable)

```python
from abc import ABC, abstractmethod

class TextEditor:
    def __init__(self):
        self.content = ""

    def insert(self, text: str):
        self.content += text

    def delete(self, count: int):
        self.content = self.content[:-count] if count <= len(self.content) else ""

class Command(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def execute(self): ...
    @abstractmethod
    def undo(self): ...

class InsertCommand(Command):
    def __init__(self, editor: TextEditor, text: str):
        self.editor = editor
        self.text = text
    def execute(self): self.editor.insert(self.text)
    def undo(self): self.editor.delete(len(self.text))

class DeleteCommand(Command):
    def __init__(self, editor: TextEditor, count: int):
        self.editor = editor
        self.count = count
        self.deleted = ""
    def execute(self):
        self.deleted = self.editor.content[-self.count:]
        self.editor.delete(self.count)
    def undo(self):
        self.editor.insert(self.deleted)

class CommandHistory:
    def __init__(self):
        self.undo_stack: list[Command] = []
        self.redo_stack: list[Command] = []

    def execute(self, cmd: Command):
        cmd.execute()
        self.undo_stack.append(cmd)
        self.redo_stack.clear()

    def undo(self):
        if self.undo_stack:
            cmd = self.undo_stack.pop()
            cmd.undo()
            self.redo_stack.append(cmd)

    def redo(self):
        if self.redo_stack:
            cmd = self.redo_stack.pop()
            cmd.execute()
            self.undo_stack.append(cmd)

if __name__ == "__main__":
    editor = TextEditor()
    history = CommandHistory()

    print("=== Text Editor with Undo/Redo ===")
    history.execute(InsertCommand(editor, "Hello "))
    print(f"  After insert: '{editor.content}'")
    history.execute(InsertCommand(editor, "World"))
    print(f"  After insert: '{editor.content}'")
    history.execute(InsertCommand(editor, "!!!"))
    print(f"  After insert: '{editor.content}'")

    history.undo()
    print(f"  After undo:   '{editor.content}'")
    history.undo()
    print(f"  After undo:   '{editor.content}'")
    history.redo()
    print(f"  After redo:   '{editor.content}'")

    history.execute(DeleteCommand(editor, 6))
    print(f"  After delete: '{editor.content}'")
    history.undo()
    print(f"  After undo:   '{editor.content}'")
```

---

### When to Use
- Undo/redo (text editors, graphic tools, Photoshop)
- Request queuing (job schedulers, task queues)
- Transaction logging (event sourcing, audit trails)
- Macro recording (replay sequences of commands)
- Remote execution (serialize commands, send over network)

### When NOT to Use
- Simple actions that don't need undo or queuing
- When commands are trivial one-liners (overhead of classes)
- When direct method calls are clearer

---

### Real-World Examples
| System | Command Use |
|--------|-----------|
| Text editors | Ctrl+Z / Ctrl+Y — undo/redo stack |
| Git | Each commit is a command with reverse (revert) |
| Redux | Actions are commands dispatched to reducers |
| Database | Transactions with rollback = undo |
| Game engines | Input commands queued and replayed |

---

### Interview Questions
1. **Command vs Strategy?** Both encapsulate behavior. Strategy: choose ONE algorithm, swap at runtime. Command: store MANY operations in a history, support undo/redo.
2. **How does Command enable undo?** Each command stores enough state to reverse itself. InsertCommand stores the text; undo() deletes that exact text. History stack tracks execution order.
3. **Command in event sourcing?** Events are immutable commands. Replay all events to rebuild state. The command log IS the database.
4. **Macro pattern?** A macro command contains a list of commands and executes them in sequence. Undo reverses the list.
5. **Command vs Memento for undo?** Command stores the delta (what changed). Memento stores the entire snapshot. Command is more memory-efficient; Memento is simpler for complex state.

## Proxy Pattern — Control Access to Objects

### What Problem Does It Solve?
You need to control access to an object — add caching, access control, logging, or lazy loading — without changing its interface. Proxy wraps the real object and intercepts calls.

---

### UML Class Diagram (Mermaid)

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class DataService {
        <<interface>>
        +getData(key: String) String
    }
    class RealDataService {
        +getData(key: String) String
    }
    class CachingProxy {
        -real: DataService
        -cache: Map
        +getData(key: String) String
    }
    class AuthProxy {
        -real: DataService
        -user: User
        +getData(key: String) String
    }
    DataService <|.. RealDataService
    DataService <|.. CachingProxy
    DataService <|.. AuthProxy
    CachingProxy --> RealDataService
    AuthProxy --> RealDataService
```

---

### Java Implementation (Compilable)

```java
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

public class Main {

    // === Service Interface ===
    interface DataService {
        String getData(String key);
    }

    // === Real Implementation (slow) ===
    static class DatabaseService implements DataService {
        public String getData(String key) {
            System.out.println("    DB query for: " + key + " (slow)");
            return "data_for_" + key;
        }
    }

    // === Caching Proxy ===
    static class CachingProxy implements DataService {
        private final DataService real;
        private final Map<String, String> cache = new HashMap<>();

        CachingProxy(DataService real) { this.real = real; }

        public String getData(String key) {
            if (cache.containsKey(key)) {
                System.out.println("    Cache HIT for: " + key);
                return cache.get(key);
            }
            System.out.println("    Cache MISS for: " + key);
            String result = real.getData(key);
            cache.put(key, result);
            return result;
        }
    }

    // === Logging Proxy ===
    static class LoggingProxy implements DataService {
        private final DataService real;

        LoggingProxy(DataService real) { this.real = real; }

        public String getData(String key) {
            long start = System.nanoTime();
            System.out.println("    [LOG] getData('" + key + "') called");
            String result = real.getData(key);
            long elapsed = (System.nanoTime() - start) / 1_000_000;
            System.out.println("    [LOG] getData returned in " + elapsed + "ms");
            return result;
        }
    }

    // === Access Control Proxy ===
    static class AuthProxy implements DataService {
        private final DataService real;
        private final String userRole;

        AuthProxy(DataService real, String role) {
            this.real = real; this.userRole = role;
        }

        public String getData(String key) {
            if (!"admin".equals(userRole)) {
                System.out.println("    [AUTH] Access DENIED for role: " + userRole);
                throw new SecurityException("Forbidden");
            }
            System.out.println("    [AUTH] Access GRANTED for admin");
            return real.getData(key);
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("=== Caching Proxy ===");
        DataService cached = new CachingProxy(new DatabaseService());
        System.out.println("  Result: " + cached.getData("users"));
        System.out.println("  Result: " + cached.getData("users"));
        System.out.println("  Result: " + cached.getData("orders"));

        System.out.println("\n=== Logging Proxy ===");
        DataService logged = new LoggingProxy(new DatabaseService());
        logged.getData("products");

        System.out.println("\n=== Auth Proxy ===");
        DataService adminAccess = new AuthProxy(new DatabaseService(), "admin");
        System.out.println("  Result: " + adminAccess.getData("secrets"));

        try {
            DataService userAccess = new AuthProxy(new DatabaseService(), "viewer");
            userAccess.getData("secrets");
        } catch (SecurityException e) {
            System.out.println("  Caught: " + e.getMessage());
        }

        System.out.println("\n=== Stacked Proxies (cache + log + auth) ===");
        DataService full = new CachingProxy(
            new LoggingProxy(
                new AuthProxy(new DatabaseService(), "admin")
            )
        );
        System.out.println("  Result: " + full.getData("config"));
        System.out.println("  Result: " + full.getData("config"));
    }
}
```

---

### Python Implementation (Runnable)

```python
from abc import ABC, abstractmethod
import time

class DataService(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def get_data(self, key: str) -> str: ...

class DatabaseService(DataService):
    def get_data(self, key: str) -> str:
        print(f"    DB query for: {key} (slow)")
        return f"data_for_{key}"

class CachingProxy(DataService):
    def __init__(self, real: DataService):
        self.real = real
        self.cache: dict[str, str] = {}

    def get_data(self, key: str) -> str:
        if key in self.cache:
            print(f"    Cache HIT: {key}")
            return self.cache[key]
        print(f"    Cache MISS: {key}")
        result = self.real.get_data(key)
        self.cache[key] = result
        return result

class LoggingProxy(DataService):
    def __init__(self, real: DataService):
        self.real = real

    def get_data(self, key: str) -> str:
        print(f"    [LOG] get_data('{key}') called")
        start = time.perf_counter()
        result = self.real.get_data(key)
        elapsed = (time.perf_counter() - start) * 1000
        print(f"    [LOG] returned in {elapsed:.1f}ms")
        return result

class AuthProxy(DataService):
    def __init__(self, real: DataService, role: str):
        self.real = real
        self.role = role

    def get_data(self, key: str) -> str:
        if self.role != "admin":
            print(f"    [AUTH] DENIED for {self.role}")
            raise PermissionError("Forbidden")
        print(f"    [AUTH] GRANTED for admin")
        return self.real.get_data(key)

if __name__ == "__main__":
    print("=== Caching Proxy ===")
    cached = CachingProxy(DatabaseService())
    print(f"  Result: {cached.get_data('users')}")
    print(f"  Result: {cached.get_data('users')}")

    print("\n=== Logging Proxy ===")
    logged = LoggingProxy(DatabaseService())
    logged.get_data("products")

    print("\n=== Auth Proxy ===")
    admin = AuthProxy(DatabaseService(), "admin")
    print(f"  Result: {admin.get_data('secrets')}")
    try:
        viewer = AuthProxy(DatabaseService(), "viewer")
        viewer.get_data("secrets")
    except PermissionError as e:
        print(f"  Caught: {e}")

    print("\n=== Stacked Proxies ===")
    full = CachingProxy(LoggingProxy(AuthProxy(DatabaseService(), "admin")))
    print(f"  Result: {full.get_data('config')}")
    print(f"  Result: {full.get_data('config')}")
```

---

### When to Use
- **Caching Proxy**: expensive operations (DB queries, API calls)
- **Access Control Proxy**: authorization checks before access
- **Logging Proxy**: audit trails, performance monitoring
- **Lazy Loading Proxy**: defer expensive initialization until first use
- **Remote Proxy**: represent remote objects locally (RMI, gRPC stubs)

### When NOT to Use
- Simple objects that don't need access control or caching
- When it adds complexity without benefit
- When the real object is cheap to create and use directly

---

### Real-World Examples
| System | Proxy Use |
|--------|----------|
| JPA/Hibernate | Lazy-loading proxies for entity relationships |
| Spring AOP | `@Transactional`, `@Cacheable` — proxy-based |
| JavaScript | `Proxy` built-in object for meta-programming |
| gRPC | Client stubs are remote proxies |
| CDN | Caching proxy between user and origin server |

---

### Interview Questions
1. **Proxy vs Decorator?** Same structure. Proxy controls ACCESS (auth, caching, lazy load). Decorator enhances BEHAVIOR (add logging, add retry). Proxy often creates the real object; Decorator receives it.
2. **Types of Proxy?** Caching, Access Control, Logging, Lazy Loading, Remote, Virtual, Protection.
3. **How does Spring use Proxy?** `@Transactional` wraps methods in a proxy that manages DB transactions. `@Cacheable` wraps in a caching proxy. Uses JDK dynamic proxies or CGLIB.
4. **JavaScript Proxy?** `new Proxy(target, handler)` intercepts property access, assignment, function calls. Used for validation, reactive systems (Vue.js).
5. **Proxy and Lazy Loading?** Proxy holds a reference to an uninitialized object. On first method call, it initializes the real object. Hibernate uses this for entity relationships.

## Architectural Patterns — MVC, MVVM, Clean Architecture

### What Problem Do They Solve?
Without architecture, business logic, UI, and data access become tangled spaghetti. These patterns separate concerns so each layer can be developed, tested, and changed independently.

---

### UML: Clean Architecture Layers (Mermaid)

```mermaid
graph TD
    subgraph "Outer: Frameworks"
        UI[UI / React / Express]
        DB[Database / ORM]
    end
    subgraph "Interface Adapters"
        CTRL[Controllers]
        REPO_IMPL[Repository Impl]
    end
    subgraph "Use Cases"
        UC[Application Logic]
    end
    subgraph "Core: Entities"
        ENT[Business Rules]
    end
    UI --> CTRL
    CTRL --> UC
    UC --> ENT
    REPO_IMPL --> DB
    UC -.-> REPO_IMPL
    style ENT fill:#2d5016,color:#fff
    style UC fill:#4a3728,color:#fff
```

---

### Java Implementation (Compilable)

```java
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Map;

public class Main {

    // ====== ENTITY (Core - zero dependencies) ======
    static class User {
        final String id;
        final String name;
        final String email;

        User(String id, String name, String email) {
            this.id = id; this.name = name; this.email = email;
        }

        public String toString() {
            return "User{id='" + id + "', name='" + name + "', email='" + email + "'}";
        }
    }

    // ====== REPOSITORY INTERFACE (Use Case layer) ======
    interface UserRepository {
        User findById(String id);
        User save(User user);
        List<User> findAll();
    }

    // ====== USE CASE (Application logic) ======
    static class CreateUserUseCase {
        private final UserRepository repo;

        CreateUserUseCase(UserRepository repo) { this.repo = repo; }

        public User execute(String name, String email) {
            if (name == null || name.isEmpty()) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Name required");
            if (email == null || !email.contains("@")) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Valid email required");
            String id = "user-" + System.currentTimeMillis();
            return repo.save(new User(id, name, email));
        }
    }

    static class GetAllUsersUseCase {
        private final UserRepository repo;
        GetAllUsersUseCase(UserRepository repo) { this.repo = repo; }
        public List<User> execute() { return repo.findAll(); }
    }

    // ====== REPOSITORY IMPLEMENTATION (Outer layer) ======
    static class InMemoryUserRepo implements UserRepository {
        private final Map<String, User> store = new HashMap<>();

        public User findById(String id) { return store.get(id); }
        public User save(User user) { store.put(user.id, user); return user; }
        public List<User> findAll() { return new ArrayList<>(store.values()); }
    }

    // ====== CONTROLLER (Interface Adapter) ======
    static class UserController {
        private final CreateUserUseCase createUser;
        private final GetAllUsersUseCase getAllUsers;

        UserController(CreateUserUseCase create, GetAllUsersUseCase getAll) {
            this.createUser = create; this.getAllUsers = getAll;
        }

        public void handleCreateUser(String name, String email) {
            try {
                User user = createUser.execute(name, email);
                System.out.println("  201 Created: " + user);
            } catch (IllegalArgumentException e) {
                System.out.println("  400 Bad Request: " + e.getMessage());
            }
        }

        public void handleGetUsers() {
            List<User> users = getAllUsers.execute();
            System.out.println("  200 OK: " + users);
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Wire dependencies (normally done by DI container)
        UserRepository repo = new InMemoryUserRepo();
        CreateUserUseCase createUC = new CreateUserUseCase(repo);
        GetAllUsersUseCase getAllUC = new GetAllUsersUseCase(repo);
        UserController controller = new UserController(createUC, getAllUC);

        System.out.println("=== Clean Architecture Demo ===");
        controller.handleCreateUser("Alice", "alice@example.com");
        controller.handleCreateUser("Bob", "bob@example.com");
        controller.handleCreateUser("", "invalid");  // Validation error
        controller.handleGetUsers();

        System.out.println("\n=== Architecture Comparison ===");
        System.out.println("  MVC:   Controller receives input -> updates Model -> View renders");
        System.out.println("  MVVM:  View <-> ViewModel (data binding) -> Model");
        System.out.println("  Clean: Entities <- Use Cases <- Controllers <- Frameworks");
        System.out.println("  Rule:  Dependencies always point INWARD toward core");
    }
}
```

